With an imminent IRA statement expected, British officials are hopeful for a new era in Northern Irish politics.
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams has urged the IRA to embrace democracy and end violence.
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern has been in talks with Adams to push for progress in the peace process.
The Good Friday peace deal of 1998 paved the way for a power-sharing assembly, but challenges remain.
Calls for the IRA to disarm and disband have intensified, with a focus on ending all paramilitary and criminal activities.
The path to lasting peace in Northern Ireland hinges on concrete actions from the IRA.
